{{Infobox scientist |name = Just Gjessing |image = |image_size = 250px |caption = |birth_date = 13 July 1926 |birth_place = [[Oslo]] |death_date = {{d-da|29 October 2005|13 July 1926}} |death_place = |residence = Norway |citizenship = Norway |nationality = Norwegian |field = [[Quaternary geology]], [[geomorphology]], [[environmental science]] |work_institutions = [[University of Oslo]] |alma_mater = University of Oslo |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = Study of [[deglaciation]], [[Governance of hydropower in Scandinavia|hydropower environmental impact assessments]], promoting [[environmental studies]] in Norway |influences = |influenced = |prizes = |religion = |footnotes = |signature = }} '''Just Gjessing''' (Oslo, 13 July 1926 – 29 October 2005) was a Norwegian geographer.<ref>[https://snl.no/Just_Gjessing Just Gjessing], [[Store Norske Leksikon]]</ref> Gjessing obtained a Ph.D. degree in 1960 with a study on Norway’s [[hydrology]] during [[deglaciation]]. One year later he was appointed full professor. In the late 1960s Gjessing became increasingly interested in nature conservation so that in the 1970s shifted the focus of his research into [[environmental impact assessment]]s. This meant leaving behind his work on pure [[fluvial geomorphology]] that had previously brought him acclaim. Following this interest he joined in 1967 the Oslo University’s Commission for Watercourse Regulation. In 1971 he became chairman of the commission while also entering the Joint Commission for Hydroelectric Power Development and Nature Conservation, of which he was a member until 1981. He co-authored various notable books including ''Beste Store Norge Atlas'' (1983) and the five volume work ''Norge'' (1984–1986) and the journal ''[[Norsk Geografisk Tidsskrift]]'' from 1979 to 1987. In the 1980s the work of Gjessing turned increasingly international with many travels to [[West Africa|West]] and [[North Africa]] where he studied environmental issues in arid and semi-arid landscapes.<ref name=Trondalen200en>{{cite journal|author-last=Trondalen|author-first=Jon Martin |date=2006|title=Professor Just Gjessing: ‘A journey with a purpouse’ |journal=[[Norwegian Journal of Geography]] |volume=60|issue=|pages=161–164}}</ref> Gjessing’s personality and approach made him subject of strong and lasting criticism from so-called “rejectionist” even within his own department at the [[University of Oslo]]. Despite their opposition Gjessing managed to establish the course Resource Geography and Landscape Ecology in 1985, attending student demands that had emerged in the 1970s about the need of courses on natural resources and environmental management.<ref name=Trondalen200en/>
